      <body>
         <listPerson>
            <person xml:id="saint-321" ana="#syriaca-saint">
               <persName xml:id="name321-1"
                         xml:lang="syr"
                         syriaca-tags="#syriaca-headword"
                         source="#bib321-2">ܐܒܪܗܡ ܢܦܬܪܝܐ</persName>
               <persName xml:id="name321-2"
                         xml:lang="en-x-gedsh"
                         syriaca-tags="#syriaca-headword">Abrāhām Neptarāyā</persName>
               <persName xml:id="name321-3" xml:lang="en">Abraham of Nethpar</persName>
               <persName xml:id="name321-4" xml:lang="en">Abraham of Naphtar</persName>
               <persName xml:id="name321-5" xml:lang="fr-x-zanetti" source="#bib321-2">ʾAḇrāhām Neptarāyā</persName>
               <persName xml:id="name321-6" xml:lang="fr" source="#bib321-2">Abraham de Nethpar</persName>
               <persName xml:id="name321-7" xml:lang="fr-x-fiey" source="#bib321-1">ABRAHAM DE NEṮPAR</persName>
               <idno type="URI">http://syriaca.org/person/321</idno>
               <idno type="FIEY">24</idno>
               <idno type="BHS">1008</idno>
               <sex value="M" source="#bib321-1">male</sex>
               <floruit source="#bib321-1"
                        notBefore="0500"
                        syriaca-computed-start="0500"
                        notAfter="0600"
                        syriaca-computed-end="0600">0500-0600</floruit>
               <note>Fiey provides the following bibliographic citations: <quote source="#bib321-1">Sa Vie, aujourd'hui perdue, fut ecrite, au VIIe siecle, par Je moine SawrTso' Rustam
(Liber superiorum, II.17). S'en inspirerent: vers 800, Je Liber castitatis (n° 43),
au XIe siecle Ia Chronique de Seert (II, 80-83), au XIIe siecle MarT ibn Sulayman
(52 arabe) qui le confond avec Abraham de Ka8k.ar, et enfin, au xve siecle,
une notice, suivie de quelques uns de ses apophtegmes, publiee par le patriarche
I. Rahmani dans sa Studia syriaca, I, 37-39, BHO, 15, traduit en franc;ais par
R.M. Tonneau dans OS 2 (1957), 337-50.
Surtout sur les ceuvres : A. Penna, "Abramo di Nathpar", dans Ia Scritti in onore di
G. Fur/ani (Rome, 1957 ; RSO 32), 415- 31 ; aussi C. Chahine, dans Augustinianum
40 (2000), 439- 60.
DHGE, I, col. 177- 78, s.v. 44.Abraham de Natfar (F. Nau).
BSO, I, 32-33 (J. Rabbi).
Sur son couvent: Fiey, Assyrie chretienne, I, 158-62.</quote>
               </note>
               <note type="abstract">Abrāhām Neptarāyā was a monk and missionary from a town near Adiabene who wrote treatises on monasticism and treatises against heresy. </note>
               <bibl xml:id="bib321-1">
                  <title level="m" xml:lang="la">Bibliotheca Hagiographica Syriaca</title>
                  <ptr target="http://syriaca.org/bibl/649"/>
                  <citedRange unit="entry">1008</citedRange>
               </bibl>
               <bibl xml:id="bib321-2">
                  <title level="m" xml:lang="fr">Saints Syriaques</title>
                  <title level="a" xml:lang="fr">ABRAHAM DE NEṮPAR</title>
                  <ptr target="http://syriaca.org/bibl/650"/>
                  <citedRange unit="entry">24</citedRange>
               </bibl>
               <bibl xml:id="bib321-3">
                  <note>His life, which is lost today, was written in the seventh century by the monk Sawrīshō' Rustam</note>
                  <title>Liber Superiorum II.17</title>
               </bibl>
               <bibl xml:id="bib321-4">
                  <note>This inspired in 800 the</note>
                  <title>Liber castitatis</title>
                  <citedRange>n°
               43,</citedRange>
                  <note>in the 11th century </note>
                  <title>Chronicle of Seert</title>
                  <citedRange>II, 80-83, </citedRange>
                  <note>and in the 12th century Marī ibn Sulaymān
                  Sulayman (52 Arabic) who confused him with Abraham of Kashkar,</note>
                  <note>one note, following some of his apophthegmata, published by the patriarch</note>
                  <author>I. Rahmani</author>
                  <title>Studia syriaca</title>
                  <citedRange>I, 37-39, BHO, 15</citedRange>
                  <note>translation in French by</note>
                  <author>R.M. Tonneau</author>
                  <citedRange>OS 2 (1957), 337-50,</citedRange>
                  <note>Above all on the works</note>
                  <author>A. Penna</author>
                  <title>Abraham of Nathpar</title>
                  <citedRange>Scritti in onore di G. Furlani, Rome, 1957, RSO 32), 415-31</citedRange>
                  <note>also</note>
                  <author>C. Chahine</author>
                  <title>Augustinianum</title>
                  <citedRange>40 (2000), 439-60</citedRange>
               </bibl>
               <bibl xml:id="bib321-5">
                  <author>F. Nau</author>
                  <title>DHGE</title>
                  <citedRange>I, col. 177-78, s.v.
                  44.Abraham de Natfar</citedRange>
               </bibl>
               <bibl xml:id="bib321-6">
                  <author>J. Habbi</author>
                  <title>BSO</title>
                  <citedRange>I,
               32-33</citedRange>
               </bibl>
               <bibl xml:id="bib321-7">
                  <note>On his monastery</note>
                  <author>Fiey</author>
                  <title>Assyrie chretienne</title>
                  <citedRange>I, 158-62</citedRange>
               </bibl>
            </person>
         </listPerson>
